<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level READ ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_agent` CONDITIONAL read access to
    `x_casemgmt_case_party` records inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.
    The condition restricts read to case_party records whose PARENT CASE is
    "Assigned only" to the calling user (i.e., parentCase.assigned_agent ==
    current user OR parentCase.assigned_group contains current user, per AAP
    Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" definition). This is the READ counterpart
    to the sibling WRITE ACL at
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml; the advanced ACL
    script body is byte-identical between the two records by design, since
    the same predicate gates both read and write access on case_party rows.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row, mirrored at the
        case_party table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at party level; case_agent can write only
        parties where parent case is 'Assigned only'" - the same Assigned-
        only predicate is mirrored for read per the AAP matrix):
            | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Read = Assigned only" cell for the
        case_party table. The "Yes" Create cell is authored by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_create_agent.xml; the "Yes Assigned
        only" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml; the "No"
        Delete cell is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_casemgmt_case_party_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-level
        ACLs are deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for an
        operation cannot perform that operation).
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - "Assigned only" definition:
            "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
             assigned_group contains current user."
        Because case_party rows do NOT carry their own assigned_group /
        assigned_agent fields (per AAP Section 0.5.7 the case_party schema
        is case, party_type, person, organization, role_label), the
        predicate is evaluated against the PARENT CASE referenced by
        current.case. The script below dereferences current.case via
        getRefRecord() and applies the same two-clause predicate
        (parentCase.assigned_agent == currentUserId, OR parentCase.
        assigned_group membership) used by the case-level and case_task-
        level agent-assigned ACLs. This ensures the operational invariant:
        an agent can read a party association if and only if they can
        read the party's parent case.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
             case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has
             full access."
        The middle clause ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") is
        the central correctness criterion of THIS file: this ACL must DENY
        read on a case_party row whose parent case has the agent neither
        as assigned_agent nor as a member of the assigned_group. In
        ServiceNow, denying read also causes the record to be excluded
        from list views, related lists, report results, and dashboard
        widget rows for the unauthorized agent - so a robust read-ACL is
        the linchpin of the entire least-privilege design at the party
        level. The validation is exercised by the round-trip-verify
        procedure (../scripts/round_trip_verify.md) in which a demo
        case_agent attempts to read seeded demo parties (Person AND
        Organization variants) whose parent case is NOT assigned to them
        - the platform must filter those rows out of every surface
        (case-form Related List for parties, party list view, any party-
        related report or dashboard aggregate). This ACL (along with the
        sibling x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned and x_casemgmt_case_task_
        read_agent_assigned ACLs) is the primary enforcement of "case_agent
        cannot access unassigned cases" - extended to parties on those
        unassigned cases.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level READ binding for the mid-tier
        scoped role on the party domain.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Polymorphic
        association via single-table choice + UI Policy): "case_party
        collapses ArkCase's two association tables (acm_person_assoc,
        acm_person_org_assoc) into one ServiceNow table with a Choice
        discriminator (party_type) and a UI Policy that conditionally
        shows person (reference->sys_user) or organization (reference->
        core_company)." Because BOTH polymorphic sub-shapes (Person and
        Organization) are stored in a single physical table, this single
        ACL record governs READ access for the case_agent role across
        BOTH variants - there is no need for separate Person /
        Organization agent ACLs. An agent assigned to the parent case
        can read a Person row's `person` reference and `role_label`,
        or an Organization row's `organization` reference and
        `role_label`, alike. All of this is gated by the single
        "Assigned only" predicate below.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "The 'Assigned only' condition for case_agent is
        encoded in the ACL condition script as a query: assigned_agent =
        current.sys_id OR assigned_group IN current.user_group_membership.
        No global ACLs are touched." For case_party the same query shape
        is applied but on the parent case row reached via current.case.
      - Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping - x_casemgmt_case_party): the
        case_party schema declares `case` as a mandatory Reference->
        x_casemgmt_case field. The script below relies on that mandatory
        constraint: a case_party row is guaranteed to have a non-null
        case reference at read time, so the parent-case dereference path
        is the canonical evaluation route. The `case is mandatory` flag
        (../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_case.xml) prevents a row
        from existing without a parent case, but defensive null-checks
        in the script body still guard against any edge case where the
        reference is somehow nil (e.g., during transient mid-save states
        or during Update-Set apply preview).
      - Section 0.5.1 ("Mirror ACL pattern at party level"): this file
        is the Read-Assigned-only instance of that mirror, paired with
        the Create-agent, Write-agent-assigned, Read-viewer, Read-manager,
        Write-manager, Create-manager, and Delete-manager siblings to
        completely populate the case_party row of the AAP ACL matrix.
      - Section 0.4.4 (User Interface Design - Internal user UI):
        "Related Lists on the case form for both case_task (parent =
        current case) and case_party (parent = current case)." Without
        this READ ACL, the case_party Related List on the case form would
        render empty for case_agent users, even on cases assigned to them
        - because related-list rendering executes a query against
        case_party that the platform filters through THIS ACL on a
        per-row basis. The party Related List is the primary surface
        through which an agent triages requesters, respondents, and
        witnesses on assigned cases; it MUST render with the correct row
        scope, which is the operational contract this ACL enforces.

    Why this is the READ counterpart to the WRITE ACL:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6 the case_agent role is granted both Read and
      Write under the same "Assigned only" condition. It would be both
      operationally inconsistent and a usability anti-pattern to allow an
      agent to write a party they cannot read, or read a party they cannot
      otherwise interact with. The two ACLs differ only in:
        - <operation>      "read" (this file)                  vs "write"
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_casemgmt_case_party.read...") vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case_party.write...")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_agent_assigned              vs *_write_agent_assigned
        - <description>    references "read" semantics         vs "write/update" semantics
      The CDATA script body is byte-identical between the two records by
      design; both encode the same predicate per AAP Section 0.5.6.

    Why current.case.getRefRecord() (NOT direct field access on `current`):
      This is a TABLE-LEVEL ACL on x_casemgmt_case_party, so at evaluation
      time the platform binds `current` to the CASE_PARTY row being read
      - NOT to the parent case. Direct access of current.assigned_agent
      / current.assigned_group would fail because those columns do not
      exist on x_casemgmt_case_party per the AAP Section 0.5.7 case_party
      schema (the party row has only case, party_type, person,
      organization, role_label). To reach the parent case's assignment
      fields, the script must dereference current.case (a Reference field
      on case_party whose target is x_casemgmt_case per AAP Section 0.5.7)
      by calling .getRefRecord() - the GlideElementReference-supplied
      accessor that returns a fully-populated GlideRecord of the
      referenced row. This is in contrast to the parallel
      x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned ACL where `current` IS the case
      row and direct field access works, and it mirrors exactly the
      pattern used in the sibling x_casemgmt_case_task_read_agent_assigned
      ACL where current.case is also dereferenced because case_task
      likewise has no assignment columns of its own.

      Defensive null-checks before .getRefRecord():
        - if (!current.case || current.case.nil()) - guards against the
          edge case where a party row is somehow inserted/updated without
          a parent case reference. ServiceNow's "case is mandatory"
          dictionary flag (../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_case.xml)
          should prevent this at the table-validation layer, but a belt-
          and-suspenders ACL check ensures the script never NPEs against
          a null reference. Returning false here defaults to deny - safer
          than throwing.
        - if (!parentCase || !parentCase.isValidRecord()) - guards
          against a stale or dangling reference where the parent case
          sys_id no longer resolves to an extant row. .isValidRecord()
          returns true only if the GlideRecord populated by
          getRefRecord() actually fetched a row from the database.
          Returning false in this branch defaults to deny - if we cannot
          prove the parent case exists, we cannot prove the agent has
          rights on it.
      Both defensive returns are intentional default-deny behavior aligned
      with the principle of least privilege.

    Why gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId) (not a manual GlideRecord query):
      The platform-supplied gs.getUser() returns the runtime caller's
      GlideUser object, whose isMemberOf(groupSysIdOrName) method is the
      ServiceNow-idiomatic group-membership probe. It internally consults
      the OOB sys_user_grmember join table and the platform's group-
      membership cache; it returns true for both direct AND transitive
      group memberships. Using it instead of a manual `new GlideRecord(
      'sys_user_grmember')` query (a) keeps the ACL script terse and
      auditable, (b) leverages the platform's membership cache for sub-
      millisecond evaluation on hot paths (form load with parties Related
      List, list-view rendering, related-list resolution during the case
      form experience), and (c) avoids the failure mode where a custom
      query forgets to filter by `user=` or `group=` and returns false
      positives.

    How this ACL composes with parent-case ACLs (defense in depth):
      ServiceNow ACL evaluation is per-table, not transitively inherited.
      Even though x_casemgmt_case_party carries a Reference to
      x_casemgmt_case via its `case` field, the platform does NOT
      automatically apply the parent case's ACLs to child party records.
      Each table requires its own role-bound ACLs to govern access. This
      file is therefore REQUIRED in addition to
      ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_agent_assigned.xml - both must apply
      for a case_agent to be able to read parties on assigned cases.
      However, by REUSING the parent-case predicate
      (parentCase.assigned_agent / parentCase.assigned_group) inside this
      ACL's script body, we guarantee operational consistency: a party
      is readable by an agent if and only if its parent case is readable
      by that agent. There is no scenario where an agent can read a
      party but not its parent case, or vice versa.

    Why <advanced>true</advanced> is REQUIRED (CRITICAL):
      The ServiceNow ACL evaluator only invokes the <script> body when
      <advanced> is true. With <advanced>false</advanced>, the platform
      evaluates only the <condition/> encoded query (which is empty here)
      and the <roles> field, granting read to ANY user holding
      x_casemgmt_case_agent regardless of the parent case's assignment.
      This would directly violate AAP Section 0.5.6 and AAP Section 0.7.3
      Gate 3 ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") and would
      reduce the agent role on case_party to effectively the same read
      scope as case_viewer (Read=All) and case_manager (Read=All),
      collapsing the entire least-privilege design. Setting advanced=true
      ensures the parent-case "Assigned only" predicate in the CDATA
      script body is actually evaluated for every case_party read attempt
      - including list-view filtering, related-list resolution on the
      case form's parties section, report row inclusion, and dashboard
      aggregate scope.

    Edge-case behavior (intentional per AAP):
      - Parties on Draft cases (parent case has no assigned_group, no
        assigned_agent): the parent-case has both fields null, so the
        first branch (parentCase.assigned_agent == currentUserId) returns
        false because null does not equal a real user sys_id, and the
        second branch's groupId is empty so the membership probe is
        skipped. The script-level default-deny clause returns false at
        the bottom. case_agents cannot read parties on Draft cases -
        which is correct per AAP Section 0.5.5: Draft is a pre-assignment
        status; cases must transition Draft -> Open (with assigned_group
        populated) before agents acquire visibility, and only then can
        parties be read under that case. The portal-submitted intake
        creates the case in Draft via the scripted REST endpoint with
        NO parties attached; party association is the responsibility of
        an agent post-Open-transition, gated by this ACL and its WRITE
        sibling.
      - Parties on Open cases (parent has assigned_group set but no
        assigned_agent): the first branch returns false (null
        assignment), the second branch checks group membership; any
        agent who is a member of the assigned_group can read the party.
        This implements the "group-level triage" pattern where any group
        member can pick up unassigned case work for their group,
        including reading party rows (witnesses, requester contact info,
        respondent organizations) before the case is individually
        assigned to a specific agent.
      - Parties on cases where the caller is the assigned_agent: the
        first branch short-circuits to true, skipping the group lookup
        entirely and granting read. This is the hot path for an agent's
        operational party visibility on the case form's parties Related
        List and avoids the cost of a group-membership probe on every
        list-view render or form load.
      - Parties on Closed cases (parent.status == Closed): this ACL
        grants read based on assignment, NOT case status. Closure does
        not revoke read access to the parties of a closed case for the
        agent who was assigned to it - which is consistent with the AAP
        intent that closed cases remain readable as a historical record
        for the agent who worked them, even though writes are blocked by
        the business rule ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_terminal_
        closed.xml on the case table itself.
      - Polymorphic sub-shape (Person rows vs Organization rows): this
        ACL governs read on both variants identically since the
        case_party table is a single physical table per AAP Section
        0.4.3. An agent reading a Person row sees `person` populated and
        `organization` empty; an agent reading an Organization row sees
        `organization` populated and `person` empty - the conditional
        UI is delivered by ../ui_policy/x_casemgmt_case_party_conditional_
        fields.xml, which operates AT THE FORM LAYER on top of this
        row-level read grant. The ACL itself does not differentiate
        between the two sub-shapes; both are equally readable to the
        assigned agent.
      - admin role: bypasses this ACL entirely via the admin_overrides=true
        attribute below. Platform administrators can always read every
        party in the scope without needing the case_agent role.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map&lt;String, List&lt;Object&gt;&gt; rolesToPrivileges`)
        keyed by the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that
        model, an "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated with
        privilege identifiers such as `acm-person-association-read` and
        `acm-organization-association-read` (because ArkCase used TWO
        separate association tables, acm_person_assoc and
        acm_person_org_assoc, each with its own read privilege), and
        the per-record "assigned only" check would have been imposed at
        runtime by Spring service classes (e.g., a SecurityFilter
        calling into AcmAssignedObject.getAssignee() on the parent
        CaseFile and comparing against the authenticated principal,
        plus an additional check against the principal's authority list
        for the parent case's assignedGroup). The ServiceNow target
        replaces this bifurcated model (declarative privilege list +
        imperative service check, doubled for Person/Organization
        sub-tables) with a single declarative scoped record-level ACL
        whose scripted condition body carries the identical predicate,
        and whose single record covers both polymorphic sub-shapes
        thanks to the case_party single-table collapse. This XML record
        is therefore the direct equivalent of TWO cells (case_agent x
        READ-PERSON-ASSOC-ASSIGNED, case_agent x READ-ORG-ASSOC-ASSIGNED)
        in the conceptual ArkCase map, unified by the polymorphic table
        design.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus a private role-name normalization step that uppercased the
        role, replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods
        with double-underscores, and prepended the constant `ROLE_`
        prefix from RolePrivilegesConstants). This entire service surface
        is replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted privilege resolver is
        needed. The role-name-normalization step in particular is
        replaced by the scoped-application convention of using literal
        scope-prefixed role names (e.g., x_casemgmt_case_agent) directly
        in the <roles> field below - no `ROLE_` prefix is prepended, no
        case folding occurs, and the role name is treated as an opaque
        identifier resolved by name against the OOB sys_user_role table.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case_party (NOT the OOB
        `sys_user_grmember` table or any other global table), and
        <roles> references the scoped role x_casemgmt_case_agent. The
        script body dereferences current.case to a row of x_casemgmt_case
        (also a scoped table); no global table is written or read for
        access enforcement (the gs.getUser().isMemberOf() probe consults
        OOB membership infrastructure as a read-only API call - it does
        not modify any global table).
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name
        / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The CDATA
        script body uses gs.getUserID() (returns the runtime user's
        sys_id, NOT a literal), current.case dereferenced via
        .getRefRecord() (resolves the parent reference at request time
        from the actual stored sys_id, NOT from any literal in this
        XML), and parentCase.assigned_agent / parentCase.assigned_group
        field accesses (resolved by the platform at request time, NOT
        by literal). The <sys_id> below is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical identifier
        "x_casemgmt_case_party.read.case_agent.assigned", a stable key
        for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the
        ACL is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-
        trip Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case_party`
        with NO dot. Field-level read restrictions on case_party are
        NOT mandated by the AAP for this role; the agent reads all
        permitted fields (case, party_type, person, organization,
        role_label) on parties of assigned cases. Field-level write
        restrictions on the CASE table's sensitive columns
        (assigned_group, assigned_agent) are authored separately in
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml - those are
        case-table ACLs and have no bearing on this case_party-table
        ACL.
      - Operation = read: corresponds exactly to the "Read = Yes
        Assigned only" cell in the AAP matrix, mirrored at the
        case_party level. The other operations (create, write, delete)
        are authored by separate ACL records or enforced by the
        deliberate absence of granting ACLs (deny-by-default for
        delete).
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or override
        scoped data without needing a case_agent role grant. It does NOT
        widen case_agent privileges - case_agents without admin still
        read only what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = true: the script body below IS evaluated at every
        read attempt (see "Why advanced=true is REQUIRED" rationale
        above).
      - condition (empty): no encoded-query condition is set; the entire
        access predicate lives in the scripted body. ServiceNow ACLs
        evaluate condition AND script (both must permit when both are
        present); leaving condition empty defers all logic to the
        script.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app
          record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml (the script dereferences
          current.case to a row of x_casemgmt_case; the table must exist
          when the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_party.xml (resolves
          <name>x_casemgmt_case_party</name>)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_case.xml (the script
          references current.case; the column must exist when the
          script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent.xml (the script
          references parentCase.assigned_agent; the column must exist
          when the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group.xml (the script
          references parentCase.assigned_group; the column must exist
          when the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's read access to seeded parties during round-
          trip verification depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml (so the
          demo agent immediately sees the seeded synthetic parties on
          their assigned cases once the Update Set commits, populating
          the case-form parties Related List with both Person and
          Organization variants)

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention. ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
    scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Allows users with the x_casemgmt_case_agent role to read case_party records ONLY where the parent case has assigned_agent=current user OR assigned_group contains current user.</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_party</name>
        <operation>read</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    if (!current.case || current.case.nil()) { return false; }
    var parentCase = current.case.getRefRecord();
    if (!parentCase || !parentCase.isValidRecord()) { return false; }
    var currentUserId = gs.getUserID();
    if (parentCase.assigned_agent == currentUserId) { return true; }
    var groupId = parentCase.assigned_group.toString();
    if (groupId && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId)) { return true; }
    return false;
})();]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>98ad89a6a3e869f11fb477ed8f8f1b87</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case_party</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_party_read_agent_assigned</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
